The accidental release prevention and emergency response management systems associated specifically with the plant's use of anhydrous Ammonia and Propane involves:

a) The integration of Safety Management Systems, devices and technologies inherent in the design of the process;
b) Use of Safe Operating Procedures and management practices;
c) Operator training and certification;
d) The ongoing maintenance of plant and equipment;
e) Preparation and testing of site Emergency Response Plan;
f) Maintenance of onsite emergency preparedness, response equipment and a trained Fire Response Team;
g) Coordinating efforts and resources with local emergency response services, and communicating with the community. 


2) Description of the Facility and the Regulated Substance Handled:  

The IGI Farmers Valley Plant processes fully refined waxes, including food and beverage grade micro crystalline waxes from various petroleum distillate feed stocks. Feed stocks and products are shipped into and out of the facility via tank trucks and rail cars. The plant has approximately 113 employees and operates 24 hours per day. There are two chemicals at the Farmers Valley plant that are subject to the RMP regulation: anhydrous Ammonia and Propane.

Anhydrous Ammonia is a toxic colorless gas with a strong pungent odor. Ammonia is used as a refrigerant to cool feedstock to the Methyl-Ethyl-Ketone (MEK) Unit. The normal maximum inventory of Ammonia is approximately 15,483 pounds. 

Propane also is a colorless flammable gas at atmospheric temperature and pressure. It has a vapor density of 1.52 (air = 1). Propane is used as a solvent to remove heavy resins from vacuum tower bottoms in the Propane De-Asphalting (PDA) Unit. The normal maximum inventory of propane is approximately198,080 pounds.


